In MFC's CString class, the `GetBuffer` function is used to obtain a pointer to a modifiable character buffer that holds the contents of the CString object. This allows you to directly manipulate the underlying character data.

The prototype of the `GetBuffer` function in CString is as follows:
```cpp
LPTSTR GetBuffer(int nMinBufLength);
```

Here's how you can use `GetBuffer`:

```cpp
CString strText = "Hello";
LPTSTR pBuffer = strText.GetBuffer(10); // Get a pointer to a buffer of at least 10 characters

// Modify the buffer directly
_tcscpy_s(pBuffer, 10, _T("Modified"));

// Release the buffer and update the string length
strText.ReleaseBuffer(); // Must be called to update the CString length and release the buffer
```

In the above example, the `GetBuffer` function is called with a minimum buffer length of 10. It returns a pointer to a buffer where you can directly modify the characters. After modifying the buffer, you must call `ReleaseBuffer` to update the length of the CString and release the buffer.

Note that `GetBuffer` will create a new buffer if the existing buffer is not large enough to accommodate the requested length. If the buffer was created dynamically using `new[]`, it will automatically handle the resizing and memory management.
